Valve's "Steambox", in your living room
17 posts
ChrisG
Ars Legatus Legionis
Registered: Apr 28, 1999Posts: 17620
Posted: Sat Dec 08, 2012 3:44 pm
If the "big picture" Steam update wasn't hint enough, apparently here's confirmation that Valve are building their own set-top box hardware :http://www.theverge.com/2012/12/8/37443 ... -steam-boxMy knee-jerk response is that it's just another console I have little interest in, but I honestly wonder where he intends to go with this. If it's not based on Windows, he now has to convince devs en-masse to *also* start writing for some kind of Linux-based....thing. And I just can't see that happening except for tiny start-up indie devs - which will condemn the entire thing to a drawn-out, slow, money-bleeding death.
krimhorn
Ars Tribunus Angusticlavius
et Subscriptor
Registered: Feb 4, 2002Posts: 9261
Posted: Sat Dec 08, 2012 4:27 pm
I posted my thoughts on Valve pushing a Linux based Steambox as being a non-starter when these rumors first came up. I can certainly see Valve designing and branding a "target" gaming/HTPC with a partner (think the Google's Nexus initiative) and holding that up as a baseline for gaming designs. I can't see them entering the full fledged console market though. That's what a Linux based box would have to be.If Valve were to enter the market as a fourth console manufacturer they'd have a steep hill to climb. History has pretty much shown that there isn't room for four consoles on the market, so unless gamers are going to completely abandon one of the existing ones it would be a non-starter. It's made a bit murkier by the fact that Nintendo has been a wide net console, picking up fewer "core" gamers but subsisting on families and "casual" gamers. So maybe there's room for a third console for the core.There's the chicken-and-the-egg problem as well. Linux has traditionally not been supported well by the AAA development community because there hasn't been a huge calling for it. If Valve wants a Linux-based Steambox to take off they would have to put a significant amount of weight behind getting developers to produce those ports so that gamers would be willing to purchase the device. That brings up the question of their Windows support: if developers see a baseline adoption of their games on Windows and are happy with that, then what incentive do they have to add another (potentially costly) port-job to the mix? If Valve deprecates or otherwise lessens their support of selling games on Windows in order to create that incentive then they're putting their entire business model at risk.So, as I said in the other thread (and at the top of this) I don't see this as being a concerted effort to create the One Box to Rule Them All, but more likely a baseline HTPC design that can be sold with their branding and running Windows. The costs of them entering into the console market whole-hog is just too high. Especially against two popular and entrenched console manufacturers. Of course the same could have been said about Sony*...*There are quite a few differences between Valve today and mid-90's Sony. Breadth of product lines, total valuation, cash on hand, etc. As a private company we don't know much about Valve's value, but I find it hard to believe that they have a warchest that's large enough for them to risk failing completely on a concerted console effort.
Troublesome Strumpet
