Posted: Sun Dec 09, 2012 12:28 pm
Actually, I think its genius. If you look at the gaming hardware market, you really have two choices. You can write for directx and get Windows and xbox. Windows is going its own way and I sure wouldn't want to depend on then if I were Steam. Microsoft is going to start wanting a cut of all software on the platform just like Apple. The other side of the coin is OpenGL. With that you get most of the other platforms. Not only can you support Steam, you could also support any Android games out there. Steam for Linux is just the test bed for the technology that will run on the SteamBox. If Valve adds good keyboard/mouse support to the system, it could attract those PC players like me who hate using controllers in FPS. Plus, being built with Linux, it allows those of us who have Linux desktops to still use our computers. They could even put out a live boot cd just to run steam on your windows pc. There are a lot of options by moving to Linux. Valve needs to be proactive now. The PC games market is not growing. I don't know if I would say its dying, but it certainly isn't doing all that well. A lot of stores like Best Buy hardly sell PC games anymore.
