krimhorn
Ars Tribunus Angusticlavius
et Subscriptor
Registered: Feb 4, 2002Posts: 9261
Posted: Sun Dec 09, 2012 3:53 pm
ChrisG wrote:That's why there isn't room for it. It already exists, and really, without custom apps, not many people really want it as much as they want a dedicated DVR / cable box.The further issue here is cost. Tivo has managed to stay solvent even though they likely have a tiny fraction of the DVR market compared to Scientific Atlanta (and every other cable-co DVR offering) but we don't know exactly how solvent they are. The majority of customers tend to purchase (or otherwise obtain) the product that has the lowest up-front cost, even if the ongoing cost makes the product with the lowest up-front the more expensive. Tivo's not a great example though, as there is no way for a customer to make a Tivo in any way cheaper than a cable-co provided DVR (upfront cost of purchasing, Tivo subscription and cable card fees all conspire against it). A dedicated console though is relevant. The Xbox 360 costs half (or more) what a much higher specced PC that can play any arbitrary game would cost. That won't change next year when the next generation of consoles comes out. If Valve wants to compete against them they have to hit the $300 base console price. That, in turn, would limit what they can do hardware wise, and (if they're to be believed that they would want an open platform) could cost them ever reaching profitability on the project since people could purchase games from whatever source they want. A Nexus-style target PC (running Windows) could work as a Steambox as it would cost them very little even if no one bought it. A push to Linux and going after the console market would be an all-in move for them. I can't see it being worth throwing away what they currently have on the off chance that five-ten years from now Microsoft might block application purchases from anywhere but the Windows Store.
